DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:

Social science perspectives on workplace autonomy represent a rich
interdisciplinary field spanning organizational psychology, sociology,
and management science. The domain is anchored by several foundational
theoretical frameworks: (1) Self-Determination Theory (SDT; Deci & Ryan,
1985, 2000) which emphasizes autonomy as a basic psychological need
essential for intrinsic motivation and well-being; (2) Job Characteristics
Model (JCM; Hackman & Oldham, 1976, 1980) which identifies autonomy as a
core job dimension affecting motivation through experienced responsibility;
(3) Job Demands-Resources theory (Bakker & Demerouti, 2007) which positions
autonomy as a key job resource buffering job demands; and (4) Labor process
theory (Braverman, 1974) which critically examines how autonomy is shaped
by capitalist production systems and management control strategies.

Recent developments include the emergence of job crafting literature
(Wrzesniewski & Dutton, 2001; Tims et al., 2012) emphasizing employee
agency in shaping their own work, proactive work design perspectives
(Grant & Parker, 2009; Parker & Bindl, 2017) highlighting employee-driven
changes, and meaningful work research (Rosso et al., 2010; Steger et al.,
2012) connecting autonomy to purpose and significance. Meta-analyses have
consistently demonstrated positive relationships between workplace autonomy
and outcomes including job satisfaction, engagement, performance, and
well-being (Humphrey et al., 2007; Christian et al., 2011).

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:

This domain provides empirically-grounded frameworks for understanding how
workplace autonomy affects human flourishing in organizational contexts,
directly relevant to examining AI's impact on workplace autonomy. The tension
between philosophical conceptions of autonomy and operational measures used
in organizational research represents a key gap our project addresses. Social
science research offers validated instruments and empirical findings but often
lacks the conceptual depth of philosophical accounts, while philosophical work
on autonomy rarely engages with workplace-specific dimensions like scheduling
autonomy, method autonomy, and decision-making autonomy that organizational
research has identified as distinct constructs.

RECENT_DEVELOPMENTS:

The past decade (2015-2025) has seen increased attention to: (1) dynamic,
within-person variability in autonomy and job crafting through daily diary
studies; (2) integration of SDT with job design frameworks; (3) proactive
employee behaviors in shaping autonomy; (4) examination of autonomy in
context of automation, AI, and hybrid work arrangements; (5) recognition of
potential negative effects of excessive autonomy (autonomy as "too much of a
good thing"); and (6) growing concern about job polarization and inequality
in access to quality work with genuine autonomy (Kalleberg, 2011).

NOTABLE_GAPS:

Despite extensive research, gaps remain in: (1) connecting philosophical
accounts of autonomy to organizational constructs; (2) understanding
mechanisms linking autonomy to moral responsibility in workplace contexts;
(3) examining how technology (especially AI) mediates autonomy experiences;
(4) addressing structural inequalities in autonomy across occupations and
demographics; (5) developing interventions that enhance autonomy while
maintaining organizational effectiveness; and (6) longitudinal studies
examining autonomy trajectories and their effects on career development
and identity formation.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:

For the state-of-the-art review, prioritize: (1) SDT as the dominant
motivational framework (Ryan & Deci, 2000; Van den Broeck et al., 2016);
(2) JCM and its extensions as job design foundation (Hackman & Oldham, 1976;
Humphrey et al., 2007); (3) Job crafting as employee agency perspective
(Wrzesniewski & Dutton, 2001; Rudolph et al., 2017); (4) Critical perspectives
on autonomy inequality (Braverman, 1974; Kalleberg, 2011). The dialectic
between employee agency (crafting, proactivity) and structural constraints
(labor process, polarization) is central to contemporary debates.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Self-Determination Theory (SDT): 11 papers - Autonomy as basic psychological need
- Job Design Theory (JCM, JD-R): 12 papers - Autonomy as core job characteristic
- Job Crafting and Proactivity: 9 papers - Employee agency in shaping autonomy
- Labor Sociology/Critical: 4 papers - Structural constraints on autonomy
- Meaningful Work: 4 papers - Autonomy as enabler of purpose
- Employee Empowerment: 3 papers - Psychological empowerment and control
- Work Engagement: 4 papers - Autonomy as antecedent of engagement
- Meta-Analyses and Reviews: 7 papers - Systematic evidence synthesis
